_... leading potentially to excesses: dividend recaps are an illustration_

Cheap debt has also helped fund managers do recapitalisations (or 'dividend recaps'), which are another (criticisable) way to provide liquidity to fund investors. The principle of dividend recaps is simple: a private equity fund acquires a healthy company through an LBO. Theoretically, this company should be sold after a few years, which was in fact not possible due to the past crisis. The leverage effect decreasing over time (the debt of acquisition being regularly repaid), there is still the option to re-leverage and distribute 'anticipated profits' to fund investors.

Theoretically, dividend recaps are putting everyone at ease. Fund managers can please fund investors with distributions, and hence prepare comfortably their next

